    <text>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_3d042e1f">
            <lb />Welte's<lb />Wonder<lb />Invention</div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_3b2e08a4">
            <lb />Welte's Orchestrion</div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_08bba70b" />
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_e806de79" />
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_2545edc4" />
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_090e558e" />

        <pb />
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_1211376e">
            <lb /><persName>Michael Welte</persName>
            <lb />The Clockmaker of Freiburg
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_e5a2870f">
            <lb />To <persName>Michael Welte</persName>,
            <lb />the chiming clock-
            <lb />maker of a dreamy
            <lb />hamlet in Germany,
            <lb />belongs the distinction
            <lb />of conceiving and build-
            <lb />ing an instrument that would reproduce the
            <lb />actual playing of a great pianist.
            <seg ana="#technical_invention" resp="#np" type="topic">
                <lb />Though a clock-maker by trade, Welte
                <lb />was given to study and invention
            </seg>
            and being
            <lb />called on to design a musical chime for a
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_f0769516">
            <lb />clock, he conceived the idea of having the
            <lb />chimes play a tune.
            <lb />On the
            accuracy and novelty of his chim-
            <lb />ing clocks, <persName>Michael Welte</persName>, in 1832, found
            <lb />the firm of <orgName>M. Welte &amp; Sons</orgName>, a venerable in-
            <lb />stitution now located at <placeName>Freiburg, Germany</placeName>.
            <lb />The years elapsed and Welte's clocks
            <lb />chimed the passage of the hours from man-
            <lb />tles in every nook of Europe, while the firm
            <lb />that had begun so humbly had acquired a
            <lb />continental prestige.
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_07d9cc5e">
            <lb />In 1849, after three years of patient toil,
            <lb /><persName>Michael Welte</persName> brought fourth his first Orches-
            <lb />trion, the clumsy forerunner of the marvelous
            <lb />Philharmonic Organs of the present day.
            <quote>
                "It
                <lb />was a wonder of mechanical perfection, con-
                <lb />taining eleven hundred pipes, that were
                <lb />brought to playing by thousands of small
                <lb />pins, representing the harmonies and melo-
                <lb />dies of musical compositions thus 'written'
                <lb />on three large wooden cylinders, that moved
                <lb />with a startling precision as had been thought
                <lb />impossible before."
            </quote>
            <lb />
            <seg ana="#technical_invention" resp="#np" type="topic">
                Many years before <persName>Edison</persName> dreamed his
                <lb />thrilling dream of the phonograph the fame
                <lb />of Welte's new invention had traveled
                <lb />through all Europe
            </seg> and soon the business of
            <lb />chiming clocks gave way to the making of
            <lb />mechanically operated musical instruments.
            <lb />Dukes and statesmen, musicians of low rank
            <lb />and high rank, came from afar to listen and
            <lb />marvel at <persName>Michael Welte's</persName> astounding crea-
            <lb />tion. The firm expanded and the business of
            <lb /><orgName>M. Welte &amp; Sons</orgName> attained large proportions.
            <lb />In 1865, <persName>Emil Welte</persName>, a son of the founder,
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_d9110567">
            <lb />Welte's Wonder Invention
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_9e212c90">
            <lb />came to America where success was instan-
            <lb />taneous. The demand for Welte's Orches-
            <lb />trions, coming now from two hemispheres, led,
            <lb />in 1872, to the removal to Freiburg, which
            <lb />thus became the musical shrine of Europe.
            <lb />Eight years later <persName>Michael Welte</persName>, the clock-
            <lb />maker closed his eyes forever, leaving his
            <lb />sons endowed with his own inventive genius
            <seg ana="#technical_invention" resp="#np" type="topic">
                <lb />In 1887, <persName>Emil Welte</persName>
                startled the world by the
                <lb />invention of a paper music-roll in connection
                <lb />with a pneumatic action,
            </seg>
            thus eliminating
            <lb />the bulky wooden cylinders and giving the
            <lb />instrument an unlimited repertoire.
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_985e1b6b" type="illustration" />
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_6dbc318f" />
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_29cfa920" type="illustration" />
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_6286a23c" />

        <pb />

        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_fd6fe9ba" type="illustration">
            <figure>
                <desc resp="#np">
                    A woman and a man sitting, listening to
                    a Welte Grand.
                </desc>
            </figure>
            <p>
                <lb />Welte's Dream of Living Music -- A Reality
            </p>
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_afba7f08">
            <lb />It was only natural that the artistic develop-
            <lb />ment of Welte Orchestrions and Philhar-
            <lb />monic Organs should have led the thoughts
            <lb />of the Weltes onward and upward to the idea
            <lb />of recording the playing of the musician
            <lb />and applying to the piano a new principle
            <lb />-that of reproducing the artist's playng
            <lb />by means of an automatic instrument.
            <lb />Thus was conceived <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon</name>* (pro-
            <lb />nounce Well-tee Mee-yon) or "Little
            <lb />Welte," as it was designated to distinguish
            <lb />it from the large instruments on which
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_d1c98342">
            <lb />the Welte reputation and business had been
            <lb />established.
            <lb />Thus <orgName>M. Welte &amp; Sons</orgName> were origina-
            <lb />tors of the idea of reproducing the playing of
            <lb />pianists, and were granted the original, basic
            <lb />patents on reproducing mechanisms now em-
            <lb />ployed in the <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon* Reproducing
            <lb />Action</name> manufactured by the <orgName>Auto Pneumatic
            <lb />Action Company</orgName>, under a license granting
            <lb />the unrestricted use of these patents in manu-
            <lb />facturing reproducing actions for the piano
            <lb />industry.
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_1a73062e">
            <lb />
            <seg ana="#exact_reproduction #secret" type="topic" resp="#np">
                Perfect Reproducing – The Secret of Welte Mignon
            </seg>
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_38047c95">
            <seg ana="#analogy_to_photography" resp="#np" type="topic">
                <lb />The <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon</name> method of recording
                <lb />a player's performance is photographic.
                <lb />Through this
                <seg ana="#secret" resp="#np" type="topic">
                    secret photographic process
                </seg>-
                <lb />possessed only by <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon,*</name> available
                <lb />only to <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon*</name> - the artist's play-
                <lb />ing is actually photographed – his tempo, his
                <lb />speaking notes, his dynamics,
                <seg ana="#soulfulness" resp="#np" type="topic">
                    those subtle
                    <lb />things that infuse an artist's very soul into
                    <lb />his playing.
                </seg>
                <lb />These photographs show precisely the pres-
                <lb />sure with which the artist strikes the keys,
                <lb />whether ever so lightly-pianissimo-or with
            </seg>
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_f403edec">
            <lb />the vigor of fortissimo.
            <seg ana="#analogy_to_photography" resp="#np" type="topic">
                And this photo-
                <lb />graphic record is so perfect–so identically
                <lb />the physical impression of the master's per-
                <lb />formance,
            </seg>
            that he is never called upon to edit
            <lb />or arrange the recording. Thus, editing the
            <lb />recording of a great pianist is not necessary
            <lb />with <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon*</name> and only with <name type="brand">Welte-
            <lb />Mignon</name> is it not necessary.
            <lb />Herein lies the vast difference between
            <lb /><name type="brand">Welte-Mignon*</name> recordings of great pianists
            <lb />and those of all other reproducing mechan-
            <lb />isms.
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_688779c3">
            <lb />The World's Greatest Pianists record for <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon*</name>
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_cec6b76a">
            <lb />Many musicians and masters whose names
            <lb />gleam like stars in the firmament of music
            <lb />have paid glowing tribute to <name type="brand">Welte-Mig-
            <lb />non.*</name> From every corner of the world come
            <lb />musicians to inscribe their matchless art on
            <lb />the imperishable pages of <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon's*</name>
            <lb />ever-growing library of music.
            <persName type="artist" corresp="https://d-nb.info/gnd/116014490">
                De Pach-
                <lb />mann
            </persName>,
            <persName type="artist" corresp="https://d-nb.info/gnd/118986724">Paderewski</persName>,
            <persName type="artist" corresp="https://d-nb.info/gnd/116204400">Bloomfield-Zeisler</persName>,
            <lb /><persName type="artist">Levy</persName>,
            <persName type="artist">Singer</persName>,
            <persName type="artist" corresp="https://d-nb.info/gnd/134788370">Pouishnoff</persName>,
            <persName type="artist" corresp="https://d-nb.info/gnd/118694820">Gieseking</persName>,<lb />
            <persName type="artist">Liebling</persName>,
            <persName type="artist">Saar</persName> and
            <persName type="artist">Boguslawski</persName>
            are but
            <lb />*Licensed under original <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon</name> patents
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_f606c738">
            <lb />a few of the great artists whose playing you
            <lb />may hear on <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon.*</name>
            <lb />The famed <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon* Library</name> of in-
            <lb />terpreted music is without a doubt the most
            <lb />comprehensive in the world of music, con-
            <lb />taining more than two thousand selections,
            <lb />embracing practically every musical compo-
            <lb />sition through which the master composers
            <lb />of the past two centuries have immortalized
            <lb />themselves.
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_6e2c7c1b" />

        <pb />

        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_36a1467b" type="illustration">
            <seg ana="#phantom_body" resp="#np" type="topic">
                <figure>
                    <desc resp="#np">
                        Semi-transparent pianist sitting at an opened
                        Welte Grand.
                    </desc>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    <lb />phantom hands of the Masters on your keyboard
                </p>
            </seg>
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_10ec60b1">
            <seg ana="#phantom_body" resp="#np" type="topic">
                <lb /><name type="brand">Welte Mignon</name> Puts the Phantom-
                <lb />Hands of the Masters on your keyboard
            </seg>
            <lb /><name type="brand">Welte-Mignon*</name> brings you living
            <lb />music. <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon*</name> makes hu-
            <lb />man the mechanical reproduction of
            <lb />music.
            <seg ana="#soulfulness #personality" resp="#np" type="topic">
                It supplies the soul and the
                <lb />personality which the individual art-
                <lb />ist puts into his playing.
            </seg>
            No one sits
            <lb />at the piano.
            <seg ana="#phantom_body" resp="#np" type="topic">
                Only the phantom<lb />hands of the masters touch the keys
            </seg>
            <seg ana="#listening" resp="#np" type="topic">
                <lb />-and you listen to the music as
                <lb />masters play it-rhythm, tone, col-
                <lb />or, quality, individuality. Just lis-
                <lb />ten!
            </seg>
            You will be amazed and con-
            <lb />vinced because the spirit of <persName>Michael
            <lb />Welte</persName>, thing chiming clock-maker of
            <lb /><placeName>Freiburg</placeName> lives in every <name type="brand">Welte-
            <lb />Mignon Reproducing Action</name>.
            <lb /><name type="brand">Welte Mignon*</name>
            <lb />The Reproducing Piano
            <lb />With the <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon* Re-
            <lb />producing Piano</name>-i.e., any piano
            <lb />*Licensed under original <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon</name> patents
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_e780b0b2">
            <lb />equipped with the marvelous <name type="brand">Welte-
            <lb />Mignon Licensee Action</name> - a selec-
            <lb />tion is played for you
            <seg ana="#virtual_presence" resp="#np" type="topic">
                with all the
                <lb />skill, warmth and color, and all the
                <lb />delicate shades of tone as though
                <lb />the pianist were seated at your piano
                <lb />in person.
            </seg> In this respect the <name type="brand">Welte-
            <lb />Mignon Reproducing Piano</name> stands
            <lb />supreme. It has no peer. It is per-
            <lb />fection.
            <lb />112 reasons why you should select
            <lb />a piano equipped with the
            <lb /><name type="brand">Welte Mignon*
            <lb />Reproducing Action</name>,
            <lb />Select a <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon* Repro-
            <lb />ducing Piano</name> first of all because it
            <lb />embodies the genius of <persName>Michael
            <lb />Welte</persName>, and then, again, select it be-
            <lb />cause 112 of America's most promi-
            <lb />nent piano manufacturers have se-
            <lb />lected <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon*</name> as the only
            <lb />reproducing action for their piano.
            <lb />This fact in itself is ample testimony,
            <lb />of the greatness of <name type="brand">Welte-Mignon.*</name>
        </div>
